segments.text: On the request of Doctor Village Mayor San Antonio.
He asked me to present to you a tape.
Of some of the reasons why I went to veterinary school where I started my type of practice and this type of thing.
I would try to put this in some kind of form.
I will also send you a copy of my resume so maybe you can.
Put it all together from this tape and also from.
my resume.
I was born and raised in Amarillo, Texas, and lived in Texas Panhandle all my life, basically a city boy.
I worked on a local ranch during the summer months, but I made most of my spending money doing construction work with a local construction company in Amarillo.
Upon graduation from

high school I joined the United States Marine Corps was in the Marine Corps for two years and after that I returned to go to Texas Tech to play in a football with the on a football scholarship I was there for a year and
Met my wife, married in 1959, and she was going to school in Amarillo at Northwest Texas Nursing School.
So I transferred back to West Texas State University and started in a general ag degree program.
While I was in general ag, I had a professor ask me what I was going to be able to do once I graduated from college.
Just being a city boy and not having a ranch background or farm background or someplace I could go, I was concerned about what my program could be.
My wife suggested I go to veterinary school since I was constantly visiting with veterinarians and going on calls with them.
So in January of 1961, we transferred to College Station to start attending Texas A&M University.
There in Texas A&M, I graduated in August 1965.
And upon graduation, I returned to Amarillo
primarily in equine practice.
During this equine practice, I also did the excess swine work and bovine work.
And during this time, I got very much interested in doing swine herd health management, which gave me a good background as far as what happened into my practice as I got into doing
bovine herd health management.
But I was there at this equine practice for nine months.
I decided I wanted to get out on my own.
So I went to a small town 65 miles southwest of Amarillo, a town called Demet.
So we moved to Demet in June of 1966 and set up a general practice.
I was the first veterinarian to ever set up practice in Demet.
There were a few that had been through Demet and done some work around Demet, but we were the first to start.
And it was fun times whenever you try to go into a small town and set up a business the way we did.
Small town of 5,000 people.
They were very open, very receptive.
and very helpful in while we were doing our practice.
While I was in Demet, the feeding industry in the Texas Panhandle started booming and therefore I started doing some so-called feedlot medicine in some of these feed yards.
There was primarily still a fire engine type calls going to
do autopsies of the dead cattle.
But as we got more involved, we became more involved in the management aspects and tried to set up herd health programs.
During all this time also, I was getting more and more involved in the swine herd health consultation.
I was doing DCAB's work out of Illinois.
They were setting up some large,
to finish operations in Plains, Kansas.
And so I was doing their work primarily in Plains.
And during this time, I was learning about how to set up a herd health management program.
Then as we got a little more involved in Dimit, we developed our practice into a three-person practice.
and I was doing more and more of the herd health management or feedlot consultation.
So in June of 1974, actually in January 1974, we sold our practice to my partner and I wanted to set up just a straight herd health consultation practice.
I stayed in Demet from January to June till the
kids got out of high school and then we transferred over to Canyon in June of 1974 and set up just a herd health consultation practice.
At this time all I had was an office and my pickup and an airplane and was doing primarily
feedlots in the 150 mile radius of Amarillo, but also had some others in South Texas and up in Wyoming.
So as we got more involved in the consultation, we also had to do more traveling.
I made a decision in 1976 to quit doing any swine consultation and devote myself to full-time
feedlot herd health consultation.
So we went from a general practice into swine and feedlot consultation practice.
Now we call ourselves adjunct manager of animal health in a herd health management program.
So we've seen several different kinds of changes in our practice and our thoughts of how we should provide veterinary medicine to some of our clients.
While I was in veterinary school, there was not anything being taught on herd health consultation, not only in swine, but definitely not in feedlots.
The feedlot industry really didn't start booming until about 1965 in the Texas Panhandle.
So I was very weak in the herd health consultation program, and the swine, like I mentioned earlier, the
The swine practice was a good stepping stone because of their advancement in the herd health consultation.
But at the same time, it made me get interested in organized veterinary medicine because that was one place to get educated.
So I was involved with the swine practitioners at the beginning, was a charter member of the swine practitioners.
and then joined the bovine practitioners right out of school in 1965.
Same way with the AVMA.
And we were constantly trying to put different programs primarily about feedlot medicine with our local veterinary association.
Then at the same time, we got involved with the Texas Veterinary Medical Association and set up

uh, feedlot committees, uh, feedlot programs, and could see where not only would, uh, herd health management consultation, feedlot management, so to speak, uh, it wasn't just tied into one type of practice.
It could be applied also into a dairy practice, into stocker practice, cow calf practice.
So there was a lot of good things were coming out of this and, and got deeply involved in,
organized veterinary medicine.
We formed a group called the Academy of Veterinary Consultants in Amarillo just for this purpose in 1972.
And so here again, this was where we started getting our education in becoming feedlot veterinarians.
Another thing that was a big problem in
herd health consultation, the feedlot medicine was the lack of records.
Most of these feedlots had some type of record system for accounting purposes, for figuring out the cost to gain, feed efficiency, and billing purposes to their customers.
But no one really had a program to set up for evaluating
the health of the animals.

So we started putting records together and trying to come up a way where we could evaluate our herd health programs and at the same time come up with a goal setting session and have some records to show whether we were going to be able to make these goals or not.
We started off with hand records.
Then we started getting into
The computer age, but prior to for floppies and laptop computers, this type of thing ever came available, we started using a DEC-10 program out of West Texas State University.
We had a telephone modem in our office hooked up straight to the West Texas State University computer office, and we developed a system called the Cadillac counting system.

this cattle counting system we can evaluate our processing programs our treatment programs evaluate the origin of the cattle and set up some good good programs and and today this thing is still existence we started this thing at first with the wt program and as we got bigger we could find out that we
needed to get off that because it cost us too much money on a monthly lease.
So we went into the small computers, the floppy disk, and the program was so large on the deck 10, it took us almost two years to get it transferred over into the floppy.
But now we do have this in use and are using it in our practice.
I use it on a routine basis myself with the feedlots that I'm consulting with.
And as far as I know, back when we did this, it was the first herd health record system designed for a feedlot herd health program.
Now as we get more and more involved in our feedlot programs,
The drug companies were coming to us to try to evaluate different products.
And so I went ahead and started a small research farm in 1979 and 1980.
I had a small facility where I could handle about 80 head of cattle.
And as the drug companies became involved and found out that I was interested in doing applied research in cattle, we started getting more requests.
And so we've grown now from 80 head capacity research facility to 2,500 head research facility.
We started out primarily doing pharmaceuticals, but now we are doing not only pharmaceuticals but biologicals.
feed additives, growth promotings, which includes the implants, this type of thing.
We started out primarily in cattle.
We did a little bit of horse research, and now we also have facilities where we can do swine research.
So it seems like we've gone in a complete circle.
Started out with general practice in Demet, built that practice up to a three-person practice.
Now we're back into a
general practice again.
One time we had six people in our program.
Now we're just back to three.
But we have a veterinarian running the general practice in town, which includes small animal, horses, cattle.
We have one veterinarian doing primarily nothing but consultation.
And then I'm doing consultation plus the research facility.
So

That kind of gives you a little bit of an idea of what we've done over the years since graduation and trying to figure out how we can be of more service to our clients and provide a good program in herd health management.
Another aspect of our business that I've been excited about was back in 1974, I was contacted by 3M Company to be a consultant with them on some new products, new ideas.
One of the ideas they had was a compressed air rifle that shoots a biodegradable bullet, which contains a life-size dry vaccine.
and use this in cattle to help eliminate some stress and some of the other things that are involved as far as when trying to vaccinate cattle in a pasture situation.
So I was consulting from them for a year and a half.
Then as this became more of a product rather than an idea, a company called Blistavet,
was formed.
A list of that is out of Minneapolis St. Paul.
Mr. Fred Paul, who put this idea together, is the one that started the company.
And he bought the rights from 3M.
And during all this time, there was about $3 million spent on just the development of it.
It took from, I said 1974, but I meant 1972.
From 1972 to about 1976, being in development, 76 to 84, it was pretty much put on a shelf and not used.
84, Fred Paul purchased the selling rights of this company and formed his own company, BlistaVet.
And in 1985, I was hired as an advisor with BlistaVet to work on this new compressed air rifle idea.
And now we have been working with them since 1985, been working on
new product development, trying to put a marketing scheme together so other veterinarians can be aware of this program and this system.
Also on the advisory stage is a FDA liaison person with my contact with the FDA from a research program and a feedlot program.
I also work with the FDA for BallistaVet in trying to
set up new protocols and get some of these products approved.
And at the same time we also, with these products, we work on the research end of it here at the research farm.
So that has been a very interesting part in trying to develop new ideas and new products.
I'm also getting more and more involved with international consultation.
This looks like this might be some value and interest as we get further and further along into our programs.
I was just just returned from South Africa and was over there for 30 days.
I was hired by a veterinarian and 14 other companies to come over
and go through their feedlot program with them.
That's one of the best unknown secrets in the world, I believe, over there.
They're the second largest cattle feeding country in the world, besides the United States and Canada.
And they've got a very viable, very interesting industry.
And I was able to go over there and spend 30 days with them, and going through their program, evaluating them,
and looking at the way they do things.
We're very spoiled in the United States.
We have a lot of biologics, a lot of pharmaceuticals, and there's things that we can do in the United States that they can't do because they don't have these products available.
At the present time, all they have is an inactivated IBR, an intradermal Pasteurella, and TSV-2 intranasal IBR-PI3.

During my visit while I was there, we also worked with the drug companies which were also help sponsoring the program and show them the type of programs we were using in the United States and some of the things they needed to do there.
So we are able to develop new tools for these people while we were there and give them some new things that they can utilize in their program.
That has been very interesting to do some international work.
Also, I'm getting involved with a society called American Society of Ag Consultants out of Washington, DC.
Here again, they have a domestic program, the United States program, but they also have a lot of international work.
So I think down the line, international consultation will be something that we as veterinarians will have to offer
to some of these other countries of some of the things that we are doing in the United States.
If you have any questions over any of this, please don't hesitate to call.
I hope these tapes will be of some value to you.
Thank you.
